en.cpp_lesson1_ex3_slide2_content:
# Send it with Arrows

By connecting items with `<<`, you can display the calculation result directly on the screen.

Code example:
```cpp
int cookies = 10;
int friends = 2;
//    
std::cout << cookies / friends << std::endl;
```
=> 5

en.cpp_lesson1_ex9_slide2_content:
# 

 `else` 


```cpp
int age = 15;
if (age >= 20) {
    std::cout << "" << std::endl;
} else {
    std::cout << "" << std::endl;
}
```

en.cpp_lesson1_ex13_slide2_content:
# Function Definition

You can group the things you want to do and give them a name.
Once created, you can run them anytime just by calling them.

Let's look at the actual code:
```cpp
// sayHello
void sayHello() {
    std::cout << "" << std::endl;
}

// main
sayHello();  // 
```

Glossary:
- `void`: Means "returns nothing"
- `()`: Parentheses that must always follow the function name
- `{}`: Write the processes you want to execute inside these

en.cpp_lesson2_ex3_slide2_content:
# Writing Functions Inside a Class

If you write a function within a class definition, it becomes a member function of that class.

Code example:
```cpp
class Circle {
public:
    int radius;
    int area() {
        return radius * radius * 3;
    }
};
```

en.cpp_lesson2_ex5_slide2_content:
# : public ParentClass

Write `: public ParentClassName` after the child class name.

Let's look at the actual code:
```cpp
// 
class Animal {
public:
    void eat() { std::cout << "eating" << std::endl; }
};

// - Animal
class Dog : public Animal {
    //  eat() 
};

Dog d;
d.eat();  // "eating" 
```

Point:
Child classes automatically become able to use the `public` features of the parent class.

en.cpp_lesson2_ex6_slide2_content:
# How Virtual Functions Work

Functions marked with `virtual` in the parent class can be overwritten by `override` in the child class.

Code example:
```cpp
class Animal {
public:
    virtual void speak() { std::cout << "..." << std::endl; }
};
class Cat : public Animal {
public:
    void speak() override { std::cout << "meow" << std::endl; }
};
```

en.cpp_lesson2_ex9_slide2_content:
# std::make_unique

You create a smart pointer with `std::make_unique<Type>()`.

Let's look at the actual code:
```cpp
#include <memory>  // Preparing to use smart pointers

// Create a smart pointer that holds an integer
auto p = std::make_unique<int>(42);

// Look at the contents (use *)
std::cout << *p << std::endl; // 42

// When it leaves this block, memory is automatically released!
```

Glossary:
- `unique_ptr`: Owned by only one pointer (exclusive)
- Leaving the scope: Going outside of the `{ }`
- Since it's automatic release, there's no need to write `delete`!

en.cpp_lesson2_ex10_slide2_content:
# Throwing Exceptions with throw

Basic form:
- `try { }`: Processes where an error might occur
- `throw`: "Throw" an error
- `catch { }`: "Catch" the thrown error

Let's look at the actual code:
```cpp
try {
    // Throw an error
    throw "error!";
} catch (const char* e) {
    // Catch the thrown error and process it
    std::cout << e << std::endl;
}
```
=> "error!" will be displayed

Points:
- When you throw an error with `throw`, it moves to `catch` immediately
- After handling the error in `catch`, the program can continue

en.cpp_lesson3_ex1_slide2_content:
# Omitting Long Type Names

`auto` is especially useful when type names are long and tedious to write.

Iterators (tools for looking through an array in order) have very long type names.

Let's look at the actual code:
```cpp
std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3};

// Without auto...
std::vector<int>::iterator it = v.begin();  // So long!

// With auto...
auto it = v.begin();  // Clean!

for (auto it = v.begin(); it != v.end(); ++it) {
    std::cout << *it << std::endl;
}
```

Points:
The more complex the type becomes, the more you'll appreciate the convenience of `auto`!

en.cpp_lesson3_ex2_slide2_content:
# Avoiding Copies

A regular range-based for loop "copies" each element as it takes it out. With large data, copying takes time.

A familiar analogy:
When reading a book, it's faster to just read the book on the shelf than to make a copy and read that every time.

How to receive by reference:
```cpp
for (const auto& x : v) {
    // Adding & means receiving by "reference" (no copying)
    // Adding const is a promise "not to change it"
    cout << x << endl;
}
```

Usage:
- `int x`: Copying is fine for small data (int, char, etc.)
- `const auto& x`: References are more efficient for large data (string, vector, etc.)

Using `auto` is convenient because it determines the type automatically!

en.cpp_lesson3_ex8_slide1_content:
# A Type Representing "Might Have a Value"

std::optional is a type that can safely represent a state of "might have a value, or might not."

Everyday analogy:
Imagine a gift box. When you open the box, it's either "contains a gift" or is "empty." `optional` represents this "box that might contain something."

Let's look at the actual code:
```cpp
// 
optional<int> find(vector<int>& v, int x) {
    for (int n : v) {
        if (n == x) return n;     // 
    }
    return nullopt;               // 
}
```

Terminology:
- `nullopt`: A special value representing "no value"

en.cpp_lesson3_ex8_slide2_content:
# How to Retrieve Values Safely

Before taking the contents out of an `optional`, check if "there is a value."

Everyday analogy:
It's like checking if there is something inside a gift box before opening it.

Let's look at the actual code:
```cpp
optional<int> result = find(v, 5);

// 1: has_value() 
if (result.has_value()) {
    cout << result.value() << endl;  // 
}

// 2: if
if (result) {
    cout << *result << endl;  // * 
}
```

Caution:
Calling `value()` when there is no value will result in an error. Always check before use!

en.cpp_lesson4_ex2_slide2_content:
# How to Retrieve the Contents

To retrieve a value from a variant, you check "what is currently inside."

Real-life analogy:
It's like checking "is it gold coins or jewels?" before opening a treasure chest to take them out.

Let's look at the actual code:
```cpp
variant<int, string> v = 42;

// Use holds_alternative to check "Is an int currently inside?"
if (holds_alternative<int>(v)) {
    cout << get<int>(v) << endl;  // Use get<int> to retrieve it as an int
}

// Trying to retrieve with the wrong type results in an error!
// get<string>(v);  // Fails because it currently holds an int
```

Key Points:
- `holds_alternative<Type>(v)`: Checks if it contains that type
- `get<Type>(v)`: Retrieves it as that type

en.cpp_lesson4_ex6_slide1_content:
# Combining All Elements

accumulate is an algorithm that combines all elements of an array into a single value.

Real-life analogy:
It's like putting money in a piggy bank every day and counting the total at the end. You can calculate "cumulative totals" or "sums."

Let's look at the actual code:
```cpp
vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};

// Add everything up (starting value is 0)
int sum = accumulate(v.begin(), v.end(), 0);
//                   Start   End     Initial Value

// 0 + 1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + 5 = 15
cout << sum << endl;  // 15
```

Arguments: (Start, End, Initial Value)

en.cpp_lesson4_ex9_slide2_content:
# Common Exception Types

C++ provides "exception classes" for common errors.

Real-life analogy:
It is like "specialized symptom windows" at a hospital. Just as the window is different for a "cold," "injury," or "check-up," you can change the response based on the type of error.

List of common exceptions:
```cpp
runtime_error     // Runtime error (general errors)
logic_error       // Logic error (program bugs)
out_of_range      // Out-of-range access (trying to look outside an array)
invalid_argument  // Invalid argument (an unusual value was passed)
```

Examples of usage:
```cpp
if (index >= array.size()) {
    throw out_of_range("Index is out of range");
}
if (age < 0) {
    throw invalid_argument("Age must be 0 or greater");
}
```

en.cpp_lesson4_ex10_slide1_content:
# The Promise to "Not Throw Exceptions"

noexcept is a keyword that declares "this function will not throw an exception."

Real-life analogy:
It is like a guarantee that "this road will never be closed." Since you can travel with peace of mind, you can choose a more efficient route.

Let's look at the actual code:
```cpp
// A function that promises "not to throw exceptions"
void safe() noexcept {
    int x = 1 + 1;  // Processing where an error will never occur
}

// A function that might throw an exception (no noexcept)
void risky() {
    throw runtime_error("Error!");  // Might throw an error
}
```

Key Point:
If an exception is thrown inside a function marked `noexcept`, the program will terminate forcefully.

en.cpp_lesson4_ex10_slide2_content:
# What are the benefits of using noexcept?

`noexcept` has two major benefits.

Benefit 1: Program becomes faster
```cpp
int add(int a, int b) noexcept {
    return a + b;
}
// The compiler can skip the "exception handling code" -> Fast!
```

Benefit 2: Moves can be used safely
```cpp
class MyClass {
public:
    // Marking with noexcept allows efficient use in containers like vector
    MyClass(MyClass&&) noexcept = default;
};
```

Real-life analogy:
If you are guaranteed at a restaurant that "this dish contains no allergens," you can order with confidence. `noexcept` is the same; by guaranteeing "no errors will occur," surrounding code can use it safely.

When to use:
- Simple calculations (addition, multiplication, etc.)
- Move constructors, move assignment operators

en.java_lesson1_ex10_slide2_content:
# Usage Patterns

Example 1: Satisfying both conditions (AND)
```java
// If score is 80 or higher and attendance rate is 90% or higher...
if (score >= 80 && attendance >= 90) {
    System.out.println("Excellent!");
}
```

Example 2: Satisfying either condition (OR)
```java
// If it's Saturday or Sunday...
if (day == "Saturday" || day == "Sunday") {
    System.out.println("Holiday");
}
```

How to remember:
- `&&`  'AND' (Both are required)
- `||`  'OR' (Either one is fine)

en.java_lesson1_ex13_slide2_content:
# How to create

When creating a method in Java, we use keywords like `public static void`. For now, just treat it as a 'magic spell' and write it as is!

Code Example: Let's create a method to greet
```java
// Create a method (Define)
public static void greet() {
    System.out.println("Hello!");
}

// Use a method (Call)
greet();  // 'Hello!' is displayed
```

Points:
- Call it by adding `()` after the method name
- You can call the same method as many times as you like

en.java_lesson2_ex1_slide1_content:
# Extending a Class

Inheritance is a mechanism to create a new class (Subclass) by inheriting features from an existing class (Superclass).

Analogy: Just as eye color or hair color is passed from parent to child, features of a Superclass are passed down to a Subclass in programming.

We use the keyword `extends`.

```java
class Animal {  // Superclass (Animal)
    void eat() { System.out.println("Eating"); }
}

class Dog extends Animal {  // Subclass (Dog) inherits from Animal
    void bark() { System.out.println("Woof!"); }
}
```

en.java_lesson2_ex2_slide1_content:
# Overwriting Methods

Overriding means rewriting a parent class method in a child class.

Analogy: Animals can "make sounds," but the sound differs depending on the type of animal, like "Woof!" for a dog and "Meow" for a cat. By using overrides, you can define different behaviors for each child class.

```java
class Animal {
    void sound() { System.out.println("Sound"); }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
    @Assets\Resources\illustrations\3d\virtual_override.png.meta  //  A mark saying "I'm overwriting this"
    void sound() { System.out.println("Meow"); }
}
```

en.java_lesson2_ex2_slide2_content:
# Declaring Explicitly

`@Override` is a marker saying "this method overrides a parent method."

Annotations are like "sticky notes" that provide additional information to the program.

Why use them?
- Prevents mistakes (shows an error for typos)
- Makes code easier to read

```java
class Cat extends Animal {
    @Assets\Resources\illustrations\3d\virtual_override.png.meta  // Declaring "this is an override"
    void sound() {  // Same method name as parent
        System.out.println("Meow");
    }
}
```

en.java_lesson2_ex4_slide2_content:
# Implementation Required

An abstract method is a method without a body. It must be implemented in child classes.

Analogy: Like deciding the rule "animals make sounds" and leaving "what kind of sound" to the dog or cat.

```java
class Dog extends Animal {
    void sound() {  // Must implement!
        System.out.println("Woof!");
    }
}
```

Difference from interfaces:
- Interface: Everything is a promise (no implementation)
- Abstract Class: Some parts are finished, some are promises

