en.java_lesson2_ex10_slide2_content:
# Protect Data

Encapsulation is a method of hiding important data with `private` and accessing it through methods.

Analogy: You cannot change a bank account balance directly. You must go through procedures (methods) like "deposit" or "withdrawal." That is encapsulation.

```java
class User {
    private String name;  // Prevent direct access

    public String getName() {  // Method for acquisition
        return name;
    }
}
```

Benefit: Prevents data from being changed without permission

en.java_lesson3_ex1_slide1_content:
# Concise Way to Write Functions

Lambda expressions are syntax for writing anonymous functions concisely.

```java
// Traditional way
Runnable r = new Runnable() {
    public void run() { System.out.println("Hi"); }
};

// Lambda expression
Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Hi");
```

en.java_lesson3_ex1_slide2_content:
# (Arguments) -> Process

```java
// No arguments
() -> System.out.println("Hello")

// One argument (parentheses optional)
x -> x * 2

// Multiple arguments
(a, b) -> a + b
```

en.java_lesson3_ex2_slide1_content:
# Processing the Flow of Data

Stream is an API for processing collection elements in order.

```java
List<String> list = Arrays.asList("a", "b", "c");
Stream<String> stream = list.stream();
```

en.java_lesson3_ex2_slide2_content:
# Various Creation Methods

```java
// From a collection
list.stream()

// From an array
Arrays.stream(array)

// Directly from values
Stream.of(1, 2, 3)
```

en.java_lesson3_ex3_slide1_content:
# Transforming Elements

**map** applies a function to each element to transform it.

```java
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3);
nums.stream()
    .map(n -> n * 2)
    .forEach(System.out::println);
// 2, 4, 6
```

en.java_lesson3_ex3_slide2_content:
# Converting to Different Types

```java
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("a", "bb", "ccc");
names.stream()
     .map(String::length)
     .forEach(System.out::println);
// 1, 2, 3
```

en.java_lesson3_ex4_slide1_content:
# Filter by Condition

filter lets through only the elements that satisfy the condition.

```java
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);
nums.stream()
    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
    .forEach(System.out::println);
// 2, 4
```

en.java_lesson3_ex5_slide2_content:
# Collectors Methods

```java
// To a List
Collectors.toList()

// To a Set
Collectors.toSet()

// String Joining
Collectors.joining(", ")
```

en.java_lesson3_ex7_slide1_content:
# A Container That May Have a Value

Optional is a type that represents the possibility that a value may or may not exist.

```java
Optional<String> name = Optional.of("Alice");
Optional<String> empty = Optional.empty();
```

en.java_lesson3_ex7_slide2_content:
# Extracting Values Safely

```java
Optional<String> opt = Optional.of("Hello");

// Get value if present, otherwise default
String s = opt.orElse("default");

// Process if value is present
opt.ifPresent(System.out::println);
```

en.java_lesson3_ex8_slide2_content:
# Four Patterns

```java
// Static method
Integer::parseInt

// Instance method (specific object)
System.out::println

// Instance method (arbitrary object)
String::length

// Constructor
ArrayList::new
```

en.java_lesson3_ex9_slide1_content:
# Sorting Elements

sorted sorts elements in their natural order.

```java
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(3, 1, 2);
nums.stream()
    .sorted()
    .forEach(System.out::println);
// 1, 2, 3
```

en.java_lesson3_ex10_slide1_content:
# Removing Duplicates

distinct removes duplicate elements.

```java
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3);
nums.stream()
    .distinct()
    .forEach(System.out::println);
// 1, 2, 3
```

en.java_lesson4_ex1_slide1_content:
# Specifying Types Later

Generics are a feature that allows you to specify the "type" of a class or method later.

Analogy: You create an "all-purpose box" first, and when you use it, you decide "this box is for strings only" or "this box is for numbers only."

```java
// T is a "type placeholder" (decided later)
class Box<T> {
    private T value;  // Stores a value of type T
    public void set(T v) { value = v; }
    public T get() { return value; }
}
```

`<T>` is called a "type parameter" and is later replaced with String, Integer, etc.

en.java_lesson4_ex2_slide1_content:
# Limiting to Subtypes of a Specific Type

By using `extends`, you can set a restriction like "only relatives of XX can be put into this generic."

Analogy: Just as only animals can be put into a "zoo cage," only number-related types can be put into a "Number box."

```java
// T can only be Number or its subclasses
class NumBox<T extends Number> {
    private T value;
    public double doubleValue() {
        return value.doubleValue();  // Can use Number's methods!
    }
}
```

en.java_lesson4_ex3_slide1_content:
# Representing an Unknown Type

The `?` (question mark) is a special symbol representing "any type is OK." This is called a wildcard.

Analogy: Like a Joker in a deck of cards, it can stand in for any card.

```java
// A method that can accept a list of any type
public void printList(List<?> list) {
    for (Object o : list) {
        System.out.println(o);
    }
}
```

This method can accept both `List<String>` and `List<Integer>`!

en.java_lesson4_ex5_slide1_content:
# Getting Key and Value Sets

By using entrySet, you can retrieve all pairs (key and value sets) in the Map one by one.

Analogy: Imagine flipping through every page of a phone book and reading out each "Name and Phone number" pair.

```java
for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> e : map.entrySet()) {
    // getKey() gets the key, getValue() gets the value
    System.out.println(e.getKey() + ": " + e.getValue());
}
// Alice: 25
// Bob: 30
```

en.java_lesson4_ex5_slide2_content:
# Syntax for Java 8 and Later

There is also a forEach method that allows for even shorter code. It is used in combination with lambda expressions.

```java
map.forEach((key, value) -> {
    System.out.println(key + ": " + value);
});
```

What is it doing?
- It executes the process "Take key and value, then display them" for all pairs.

Which one to use?
- entrySet: Works even in older versions of Java
- forEach: Short and readable (Java 8 and later)

en.java_lesson4_ex7_slide1_content:
# Defining Natural Ordering

By implementing Comparable, you can define a "natural ordering" for objects.

Analogy: Just as numbers have a natural order like "1 < 2 < 3", you can tell a class you created, "Please arrange yourself in this order."

```java
class Person implements Comparable<Person> {
    String name;
    public int compareTo(Person other) {
        // Compare by name in alphabetical order
        return this.name.compareTo(other.name);
    }
}
```

en.java_lesson4_ex7_slide2_content:
# Meaning of the Return Value

The `compareTo` method returns the comparison result as a number.

Rules:
- `this < other`  Returns a negative number (self comes first)
- `this == other`  Returns 0 (same order)
- `this > other`  Returns a positive number (other comes first)

Example: Comparing by age
```java
return this.age - other.age;
// 25 - 30 = -5 (Negative  self comes first)
// 30 - 30 = 0  (0  same)
// 35 - 30 = 5  (Positive  other comes first)
```

en.java_lesson5_ex2_slide2_content:
# Used for Cleanup Processing

Write "cleanup" tasks like closing a file or disconnecting in the `finally` block.

Analogy: It's like remembering to put a book back on the shelf when you're done reading, or turning off the lights.

```java
FileReader reader = null;
try {
    reader = new FileReader("file.txt");
    // File reading process
} finally {
    if (reader != null) reader.close();  // Always close!
}
```

Benefit: You won't forget the cleanup even if an error occurs.

en.java_lesson5_ex3_slide1_content:
# Passing Exceptions to the Caller

`throws` is a keyword that declares, "This method might throw an exception."

Analogy: It's like putting a warning note that says, "This ball might explode, so whoever catches it, be careful."

```java
public void readFile() throws IOException {
    // File reading process
    // IOException (input/output error) might occur!
}
```

en.java_lesson5_ex3_slide2_content:
# Catch or Rethrow (Passing On)

The side calling a method with `throws` chooses to either "catch" it or "throw it further up."

Method 1: Catch it yourself
```java
try {
    readFile();  // Exception might occur
} catch (IOException e) {
    // Handle it yourself
}
```

Method 2: Throw it further up
```java
public void caller() throws IOException {
    readFile();  // Don't handle it yourself; leave it to the caller
}
```

Analogy: When a problem arises, it's a choice between "solving it yourself" or "reporting it to your boss."

en.java_lesson5_ex4_slide1_content:
# Defining Your Own Exceptions

You can create your own original exception by inheriting from `Exception`.

Analogy: Standard exceptions are "general errors," while custom exceptions are "errors specific to this app." You can create a special error like "Negative age is invalid!"

```java
class MyException extends Exception {  // Inherit from Exception
    public MyException(String msg) {
        super(msg);  // Pass the message to the parent class
    }
}
```

en.java_lesson5_ex5_slide1_content:
# try-with-resources

Since Java 7, there is a convenient way to write code that automatically closes resources (like files).

Analogy: It's like a system where if you borrow a library book, it's automatically returned when the due date arrives.

```java
try (FileReader reader = new FileReader("file.txt")) {
    // Process using reader
}  // close() is automatically called here!
```

The key is to declare the resource inside the `()` (parentheses).

en.java_lesson5_ex5_slide2_content:
# No `finally` Needed

Previously, you had to close resources manually in a `finally` block, but with `try-with-resources`, it's automatic.

Traditional Way (Long)
```java
FileReader r = null;
try {
    r = new FileReader("file.txt");
} finally {
    if (r != null) r.close();  // Manual close
}
```

try-with-resources (Short!)
```java
try (FileReader r = new FileReader("file.txt")) {
    // Process
}  // Automatically closed!
```

Benefit: No more forgotten closes, and the code is simpler!

en.java_lesson5_ex10_slide1_content:
# Catching Multiple Exceptions Together

From Java 7 onwards, you can catch multiple exceptions together using the | (pipe symbol).

Analogy: Just like "picking up apples or oranges if they fall," you can handle multiple types together.

```java
try {
    // Process
} catch (IOException | SQLException e) {  // If either occurs
    // Both exceptions are processed the same way
}
```

Writing exceptions that require the same processing together makes the code much cleaner!

en.java_lesson5_ex10_slide2_content:
# Catching in Order

If you want to perform different processing for each type of exception, write multiple catch blocks.

```java
try {
    // Process
} catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
    // Process for when the file is not found
} catch (IOException e) {
    // Process for other I/O errors
}
```

Important rule: Write specific exceptions first and general exceptions later.

Why? Because if you write the general ones first, they will catch the specific ones too, and you won't be able to distinguish between them.

en.c_lesson1_ex1_slide2_content:
# The First "Magic Spell" to Write

To run C, there are certain "rules" you must always write.

1. #include <stdio.h> (Include Standard I/O)
```c
#include <stdio.h>
```
This is a spell to prepare the "tools for showing text on the screen." Think of it like borrowing a book from a library!

2. int main() (Int Main)
```c
int main() { ... }
```
This is the signal that "this is where the program starts!" It's like the "Chapter 1" of a book.

Let's look at the actual code:
```c
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    printf("C is fun!\n");
    return 0;
}
```

`printf` (print-f) is a command that says "please display this text on the screen."
`return 0` (return-zero) is a report saying "everything went well!"

Let's remember this structure!

en.c_lesson1_ex12_slide2_content:
# Creating Your Own Type

`struct` means "structure" in English.

Using the word `struct`, you can create a blueprint for a new "box" that groups multiple variables together.

Let's look at some actual code:
```c
// Create a blueprint for book information
struct Book {
    int price;  // Price
};

// Use the blueprint to create an actual "book"
struct Book b = {500};  // A 500-yen book
printf("%d\n", b.price);  // Display the book's price
```
=> 500 will be displayed

Key Point:
You access the data inside using a dot `.`, like `b.price`.

en.c_lesson1_ex13_slide2_content:
# Grouping Procedures

You can group things you want to do and give them a name.
Once created, you can run them anytime just by calling them.

Let's look at some actual code:
```c
// Create (define) a function called "aisatsu"
void aisatsu() {
    printf("Yoo-hoo\n");
}

// Call (use) it inside main
aisatsu();  // This displays "Yoo-hoo"
```

Key Points:
- `void` means "returns nothing"
- It is a rule to put parentheses `()` after the function name
- You write the processes you want to perform inside `{ }`

en.c_lesson2_ex3_slide2_content:
# Defining Arguments Inside Parentheses

Write arguments inside the () after the function name. Specify the type and name.

Code Example:
```c
void greet(int age) {
    printf("%d years old\n", age);
}

greet(10); // 10 years old
```

en.c_lesson2_ex4_slide2_content:
# Returning Results by Specifying Types

Write the return value type before the function name. `void` means no return value, and `int` returns an integer.

Code Example:
```c
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int result = add(3, 5); // 8
```

en.c_lesson2_ex7_slide2_content:
# Receiving a Pointer in a Function

By making a function argument a pointer and passing the address with `&` when calling it.

Code Example:
```c
void add_ten(int *p) {
    *p = *p + 10;
}

int x = 5;
add_ten(&x);
printf("%d\n", x); // 15
```

en.c_lesson2_ex8_slide2_content:
# stdlib.h Required

Allocate memory with `malloc(size)` and receive it as a pointer. Be sure to release it with `free`.

Code Example:
```c
#include <stdlib.h>
int *p = malloc(sizeof(int));
*p = 100;
printf("%d\n", *p);
free(p);
```

en.c_lesson2_ex9_slide2_content:
# Accessing Members from a Pointer

To access a member from a structure pointer, use `->`. `(*p).x` and `p->x` mean the same thing.

Code Example:
```c
struct Point { int x; int y; };
struct Point pt = {3, 4};
struct Point *p = &pt;
printf("%d\n", p->x); // 3
```

en.c_lesson3_ex1_slide1_content:
# Pointers to Functions

A function pointer is a variable that can store the address of a function.

```c
int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }

// Function pointer declaration
int (*fp)(int, int);
fp = add;
```

en.c_lesson3_ex3_slide1_content:
# 1 if Both are 1

`&` results in 1 only if both bits are 1.

```c
// 5 = 0101
// 3 = 0011
// -------
// 1 = 0001
int result = 5 & 3;  // 1
```

en.c_lesson3_ex4_slide1_content:
# 1 if Either is 1

| results in 1 if either bit is 1.

```c
// 5 = 0101
// 3 = 0011
// -------
// 7 = 0111
int result = 5 | 3;  // 7
```

en.c_lesson3_ex7_slide1_content:
